posts.name: Rustomac
posts.cooked: Our team has faced challenges with accurate hole placement using our current tube jig setup this season. With time and funds available during the off-season, we aim to enhance our setup with something highly reliable. We’re considering the **WCP** (West Coast Products) tube jig. Are there key factors to evaluate before purchasing? Concerns regarding bearing alignment may arise if tubes are paralleled due to uneven or excessive clamping; how does this affect performance on the Omio X8? Thank you for your insights!
Do not output anything but the cleaned version.

posts.name: Sam Viesselman
posts.cooked: Every piece of tubing on our robot was made using our WCP Tube Jig this year, and we thoroughly enjoyed it. We encountered a few issues with the cam bolts on the clamps, but those were promptly addressed by training the students to avoid overtightening. While constructing our own solution was considered, after accounting for materials and time savings, purchasing from WCP West Coast Products proved more efficient.

posts.name: Stewart Riley
posts.cooked: We’ve had it for several years now and continue to perform exceptionally well. We utilize it regularly for precise tasks like drilling bearing holes and creating exact mounting holes, as well as for weight reduction. We strongly recommend purchasing extra components such as cam bolts and clamp blocks since they tend to wear out over time. Our final assessment is that it is highly reliable, accurate, and straightforward to operate.

posts.name: Saber_8871
posts.cooked: We haven't dealt with this issue before, but we'd be interested in your thoughts. Does anyone know if this setup can work on routers aside from the Oimo model? It seems like you could input tracks into a router if it has them, but it's not immediately clear just by looking at one image. Additionally, securing tubing across different applications has been a challenge, and having a secure jig would be helpful.

posts.name: Tom Praisner
posts.cooked:
We purchased a Shapeoko 5 Pro 48" x 48" with the 700W spindle this past summer and have been impressed with its performance. It offers a large work area that allows us to route multiple materials efficiently. Our routing process involves using aluminum on it regularly, particularly for creating three belly pans measuring approximately 30" x 30", which keeps our router stationary during long cutting sessions. Additionally, we utilize a set of aluminum bars mounted on the routing table for consistent material handling.

For coolant and lubrication, we employ an Amazon-made 70% isopropyl alcohol solution. We pair this with a dust collection system comprising a Shapeoko dust boot and a stealthonic Dewalt shop vac, allowing us to work comfortably without needing additional cleaning supplies during the day. Our router remains functional throughout the day and enables conversation with friends nearby while working beside it. 

We maintain an online presence through our OA blog, which documents our progress and experiences with the robot and various projects. Unfortunately, the Shapeoko requires maintenance every few months due to tool bit wear, though it has proven reliable overall.

posts.name: Sam Knight
posts.cooked: We have settled on an effective and neat arrangement for coolant/lubrication using an airbrush compressor paired with an inexpensive mister from Amazon, running 70% isopropyl alcohol. We would love to hear more about this setup. Our Shapeoko 3XXL currently relies on manually sprayed WD40, though it works well enough, though it eventually causes our spoiled board to overflow and is not ideal when combined with the “sweepy” dust extractor, particularly during high-volume operations like pocketing.

posts.name: David B
posts.cooked: Me too, my team has a 3XXL and a 5 Pro.

posts.name: Tom Praisner
posts.cooked: The compressor, mist system, and tubing we used were all purchased from Amazon. The compressor effectively moves chips while delivering a coolant mist, using 70% isopropyl alcohol (ISA) and 30% water. The mist evaporates quickly, preventing chips from sticking to the cut and keeping the aluminum cool. A "Sweepy" with a shop vac was used; pushing the mist nozzle through the dust boot eliminated chip binding. Cleanup was minimal, with the setup being simple and cost-effective. The images show a reservoir of Isa attached to the machine, providing enough mist for an extended period.
